\subsection{Time-of-Arrival Crossmatching}
\label{sec:toa}

Before attributing the dispersion and scattering budgets we verify that the
twelve events are genuine co-detections---the same burst seen by both
facilities, with arrival times consistent under the cold-plasma dispersion law
and the geometric light-travel delay between the sites. The wide baseline
between CHIME/FRB (400--800\,MHz) and DSA-110 ($\sim$1.4\,GHz) makes the
co-detections a test of the $1/\nu^2$ dispersion scaling and of the relative
timing alignment of the two facilities \citep{Lorimer2007, Thornton2013}.

\subsubsection{Delay model}

We translate the arrival times at the two central frequencies to a common
reference frequency $\nu_{\mathrm{ref}}=400$\,MHz. The cold-plasma dispersion
delay is
\begin{equation}
\Delta t_p = K_{\mathrm{DM}}\,\mathrm{DM}
\left(\frac{1}{\nu_{\mathrm{ref}}^2}-\frac{1}{\nu_{\mathrm{obs}}^2}\right),
\label{eq:dmdelay}
\end{equation}
with $K_{\mathrm{DM}} = 4.148808\times10^{3}\,\mathrm{MHz^2\,pc^{-1}\,cm^3\,s}$.
The geometric light-travel difference between the observatories is
\begin{equation}
\tau_{\mathrm{geo}} = \frac{(\mathbf{p}_2-\mathbf{p}_1)\cdot\hat{\mathbf{s}}}{c},
\label{eq:geodelay}
\end{equation}
where $\mathbf{p}_1$ and $\mathbf{p}_2$ are the GCRS position vectors of CHIME
and DSA-110 and $\hat{\mathbf{s}}$ is the unit vector toward the source. The
timing residual $\mathcal{R}=\Delta\tau_{\mathrm{obs}}-\tau_{\mathrm{geo}}$ is
the difference between the frequency-corrected inter-site offset and the
predicted geometric delay; a residual of zero indicates perfect agreement.

\subsubsection{Residuals and systematics}

Across the sample the residuals (Figure~\ref{fig:toa_resid}) have a mean of
$2.42$\,ms, a standard deviation of $3.06$\,ms, and a median of $1.88$\,ms,
consistent with the combined timing uncertainties of the two instruments, which
are dominated by coarse time resolution and pulse-width variation. A systematic
search for correlations between the residuals and burst properties
(Figure~\ref{fig:toa_sys}) finds none that reach significance: the residual is
uncorrelated with DM ($r=0.14$, $p=0.67$) over the observed range
$262$--$959$\,pc\,cm$^{-3}$, confirming the adopted $1/\nu^2$ scaling and the
value of $K_{\mathrm{DM}}$; the correlations with FWHM ($r=0.48$, $p=0.11$) and
combined measurement uncertainty ($r=0.49$, $p=0.11$) are moderate but not
significant, as expected since wider bursts time less precisely; and a
suggestive anti-correlation with epoch ($r=-0.54$, $p=0.07$) warrants monitoring
for long-term clock or baseline drift as the sample grows. The per-burst
properties and residuals are listed in Table~\ref{tab:toa}.

\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{toa_crossmatch_analysis_premium}
\caption{Time-of-arrival residuals for the twelve co-detections. Left: residual
(measured $-$ geometric) per burst, colored by DM, with the median $1\sigma$
timing uncertainty ($\pm2.5$\,ms) shaded. Right: residual versus DM with a
linear fit ($r=0.14$).}
\label{fig:toa_resid}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure*}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{systematics_check_matrix}
\caption{Systematic correlation search. Residuals versus DM, FWHM, combined
measurement uncertainty, and epoch (MJD), with Pearson $r$ and trend lines. No
correlation reaches significance ($p<0.05$).}
\label{fig:toa_sys}
\end{figure*}

